![A tasty-looking ceviche](/assets/images/lessons/knife-skills/ceviche-5.jpg)

Understandably, once you’ve _learned_ to use a _chef’s knife_, you want to use it. And you _want something fancier_ to show for it. Here’s a recipe for a dish that _seems fancy_ but is in fact _very easy_. While it _does not require cooking_, it does present _ample opportunity_ to _practice_ your _knife work_.

_Ceviche_ is just _fish_ prepared in a _bath of citrus juice_. Some people say “cooked” or “cured”. It’s actually a _chemical process_ called _denaturing_, which _breaks_ many of the _bonds_ that hold _protein molecules_ in their shape. The _acid_ of _lemon or lime_ changes the _fish’s flesh_ from its plush, raw, _translucent state_ to an _opaque firmness_ (and flavours it as well). The _type_ of fish _doesn’t matter_. Sea bream, tuna, arctic char or halibut all _work fine_. So long as it _isn’t_ a really _dense fish_, like pickerel or catfish. It just has to be _as fresh as possible_.

